Scenario 001 - Nmap Reconnaissance Detection (Suricata)

Overview

This scenario demonstrates how different Nmap reconnaissance techniques generate alerts in Suricata. Three progressively more advanced scans were executed from the Exegol attack platform against the Windows 11 victim.

Attacker: Exegol (10.10.4.1)

Target: Windows 11 (10.10.6.2)

IDS: Suricata (pfSense)

⸻

Scenario 1 - SYN Scan

Command

nmap -Pn -sS 10.10.6.2

Description

Performs a TCP SYN (“half-open”) scan to identify open TCP ports without completing the full TCP handshake.

Purpose

* Discover open ports
* Fast reconnaissance
* Low network footprint

⸻

Scenario 2 - Service Version Detection

Command

nmap -Pn -sV 10.10.6.2

Description

Performs service detection on open ports by sending application-specific probes to identify the running software and version.

Purpose

* Identify running services
* Detect software versions
* Gather information for further exploitation

⸻

Scenario 3 - Aggressive Scan

Command

nmap -Pn -sS -T5 -A --reason 10.10.6.2

Description

Performs an aggressive reconnaissance combining multiple Nmap features into a single scan.

Enabled Features

* TCP SYN Scan (-sS)
* OS Detection (-O)
* Service Version Detection (-sV)
* Default NSE Scripts (-sC)
* Traceroute
* Fast Timing Template (-T5)
* Displays scan reasoning (--reason)

Purpose

* Comprehensive host fingerprinting
* Operating system identification
* Service enumeration
* Network path discovery
* Application and protocol fingerprinting

⸻

Summary

Scenario	Command	Objective
Scenario 1	nmap -Pn -sS 10.10.6.2	TCP SYN reconnaissance
Scenario 2	nmap -Pn -sV 10.10.6.2	Service version detection
Scenario 3	nmap -Pn -sS -T5 -A --reason 10.10.6.2	Aggressive reconnaissance and fingerprinting

These three scenarios were executed to evaluate Suricata’s detection capabilities against increasingly detailed reconnaissance activity performed with Nmap.
